# Known Pitfalls

## 1. SCSS `&` Parent Selector

Never use `&` to reference outer ancestors in deep nesting.

```scss
// WRONG — produces `.modifier .outer .inner`
.outer {
	.inner {
		.modifier & {
		}
	}
}

// RIGHT — keep selectors flat or restructure
.modifier .outer .inner {
}
```

Also avoid `&__` / `&--` SCSS nesting shorthand in block SCSS — and do not use BEM `__` class names at all. Every rule lives nested inside the outer `.{slug}-section` wrapper, using **plain child class names**. Modifiers keep the `--` suffix and are written in full (no `&--` shorthand).

```scss
// ❌ WRONG — BEM class names and `&__` shorthand
.home-hero {
	&__title {
	}
	&__cta {
	}
}
.home-hero__title {
}
.home-hero__cta {
}

// ✅ RIGHT — nested inside the section wrapper, plain child names
.home-hero-section {
	.title {
	}
	.cta {
	}
	.tag--dark {
	} // modifier written in full, never `&--dark`
}
```

## 2. `.img-cover` Class

Uses `position: absolute`. Only use on full-bleed images inside a `.img-cover-block` wrapper. Never on small contained images.

```php
// CORRECT
<div class="img-cover-block">
	<?php echo wp_get_attachment_image( $image_id, 'w768', false, [ 'class' => 'img-cover' ] ); ?>
</div>
```

## 3. Block JSON Field Keys

Always prefix field keys: `field_{block_slug}_{field_name}`

```json
// WRONG
{ "key": "field_title" }

// RIGHT
{ "key": "field_hero_slider_title" }
```

## 4. Auto-Injected Fields

Settings / Spacing / Display / Custom CSS / Classes / Unique ID are auto-injected at block registration. Never add these to the block's `.json` file.

## 5. Swiper Inside Flex/Grid Parent

Flex/grid children default to `min-inline-size: auto`, preventing shrink below content width. Swiper expands to fit all slides, breaking scroll.

**Fix:** Add `min-inline-size: 0` to the `.swiper` element.

```scss
.swiper {
	min-inline-size: 0;
}
```

## 6. SVG Helper

Use `skel_get_svg()`. The `skel_svg()` function is deprecated and removed.

```php
// WRONG
echo skel_svg( 'arrow-right' );

// RIGHT
echo skel_get_svg( 'arrow-right', array( 'aria-hidden' => 'true' ) );
```

## 7. Always Use WordPress Built-in Functions First

**MUST** use native WordPress functions before writing custom code. Never implement a custom solution when WordPress already provides one.

```php
// WRONG — custom slug check
$slug = get_post_field( 'post_name', get_queried_object_id() );
if ( in_array( $slug, array( 'contact', 'contact-us' ), true ) ) { }

// RIGHT — built-in WordPress conditional
if ( is_page( array( 'contact', 'contact-us' ) ) ) { }
```

Common built-ins to use:

- `is_page()`, `is_single()`, `is_archive()`, `is_home()`, `is_front_page()` — page conditionals
- `get_permalink()`, `get_the_ID()`, `get_queried_object()` — post/page data
- `wp_get_attachment_image()`, `wp_get_attachment_url()` — media
- `get_template_part()` — template inclusion
- `wp_enqueue_script()`, `wp_enqueue_style()` — asset loading

Check the [WordPress Function Reference](https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/) before writing custom logic.

## 9. Guard foreach Arrays

Always check that an array is not empty before iterating with `foreach`. Missing this causes PHP warnings when the field returns `null` or `false`.

```php
// WRONG — no guard
foreach ( $items as $item ) { }

// RIGHT — guard with is_array + ! empty
if ( is_array( $items ) && ! empty( $items ) ) :
	foreach ( $items as $item ) : ?>
		...
	<?php endforeach;
endif;
```

Use `?? array()` only when iterating **without** a guard, so the variable is always a safe type:

```php
// No guard — need ?? array() to avoid warning
$items = get_field( 'items' ) ?? array();
foreach ( $items as $item ) { ... }

// Guard present — ?? array() is redundant, skip it
$items = get_field( 'items' );
if ( is_array( $items ) && ! empty( $items ) ) {
	foreach ( $items as $item ) { ... }
}
```

## 8. SCSS Block Import — Always `abstracts-blocks`

Block SCSS files must import **`abstracts-blocks`**, not `abstracts`. If you see `abstracts` (without `-blocks`) in a block file, it's a bug — correct it. Do not "match what's already in the file" — the correct form is always `abstracts-blocks` in block SCSS.

```scss
// ✅ CORRECT — in every blocks/{slug}/{slug}.scss
@use '../../src/sass/partials/abstracts-blocks' as *;

// ❌ WRONG — missing -blocks suffix
@use '../../src/sass/partials/abstracts' as *;
```

## 10. Using `@media` to Change Values Instead of `fluid()`

`@media` is for **layout changes** (grid columns, flex direction, show/hide, position). It is **not** for changing values like font-size, padding, gap, or margin — those should use `fluid(min, max)`. If the only thing changing at a breakpoint is a numeric value, rewrite with `fluid()`.

```scss
// ❌ WRONG — @media used to tweak a value
.title {
	font-size: rem-calc(18);

	@media (width >= $md) {
		font-size: rem-calc(28);
	}
}

// ✅ RIGHT — fluid() handles the scale
.title {
	font-size: fluid(18, 28);
}
```

Reserve `@media` for things that genuinely restructure the layout (e.g. 1 column → 3 columns, stacked → side-by-side).

Also: **always mobile-first** (`width >= $bp`), never desktop-first (`width < $bp`). Write the mobile layout as the default, then progressively enhance for larger screens.

## 11. Never Use `nl2br()`

Don't wrap output in `nl2br()`. Use `white-space: pre-line` in CSS instead.

```php
// ❌ wp_kses_post( $description )
// ✅ wp_kses_post( $description )
```
